<div class="entry-header">
<h2 itemprop="name">
How to check whether your site is mobile friendly? </h2>
<dl class="article-info">
<dt class="article-info-term"></dt>
<dd class="createdby" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
<i class="fa fa-user"></i>
<span itemprop="name" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Written by ">Arafat Bin Sultan</span> </dd>
<dd class="category-name">
<i class="fa fa-folder-open-o"></i>
<a href="/blog" itemprop="genre" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Article Category">Blog</a> </dd>
<dd class="comment">
<i class="fa fa-comments-o"></i>
<span class="comments-anchor">
<a href="https://shapebootstrap.net/blog/11-how-to-check-whether-your-site-is-mobile-friendly#disqus_thread"></a>
</span>
</dd>
<dd class="create">
<i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i>
<time datetime="2015-08-25T14:50:13+06:00" itemprop="dateCreated" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Created Date">
25 August 2015 </time>
</dd>
<dd class="hits">
<span class="fa fa-eye"></span>
<meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserPageVisits:892"/>
Hits: 892</dd>
</dl>
</div>
<div itemprop="articleBody">
<p>Started from April 21 2015, search giant Google now uses mobile friendliness as a signal for ranking websites. In plain text, if your site is mobile friendly, Google will <a href="http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2015/02/finding-more-mobile-friendly-search.html" target="_blank">award </a>it with a better ranking while listing in mobile search results. <a href="https://blogs.bing.com/webmaster/2015/05/14/our-approach-to-mobile-friendly-search/" target="_blank">Bing </a>has also introduced 'Mobile-Friendly' tag in search results. So, as a webmaster or site owner, you must ensure that your site renders well on mobile browsers. But how to test it? Here are top three tools to do that.</p>
<p> </p>
<h3><a href="https://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/mobile-friendly/" target="_blank">1. Google Mobile-Friendly Test</a></h3>
<p><img src="/images/blog/mobile-friendly-test/mobilefriendly3.png" alt="" width="1238" height="383"/></p>
<p>You can check any website's mobile-friendliness in seconds with this tool. Just visit the utility page, enter the target site URL into the box and click the Analyze button. The system will check the site and let you know whether the page is mobile friendly or not. A mobile emulated view of the site will be shown as well.</p>
<h3><a href="https://developers.google.com/speed/pagespeed/insights/" target="_blank">2. PageSpeed Insights</a></h3>
<p><img src="/images/blog/mobile-friendly-test/gmailgooglespeed3.png" alt="" width="1140" height="653"/></p>
<p>This one is also provided by Google. PageSpeed Insights differs from Mobile-Friendly Test tool in the way they display the results. Mobile-Friendly Test won't score the site performance in numbers. But PageSpeed Insights will show a score earned by the target site according to its mobile compatibility and usability. This score is very important to stay informed and take necessary actions to keep the site fast and compatible across major platforms. This tool also displays a mobile view of the testing site.</p>
<h3><a href="http://validator.w3.org/mobile/" target="_blank">3. W3C mobileOK Checker</a></h3>
<p><img src="/images/blog/mobile-friendly-test/w3cmobile2.png" alt="" width="1351" height="734"/></p>
<p>World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) presents an online mobile validator tool that performs several tests on a target web page and generates a report based on the findings. A page gets the 'mobileOK' status if it passes those all tests. Here you can also upload/input your site elements/sources to validate online. </p>
<h3>Bonus</h3>
<p>The above three tools should be enough to find whether your site is mobile friendly or not. Moreover, you can see your site live on different virtual mobile screens to check how it renders on small gadgets. There are lots of tools for this. I've tried a Chrome extension called '<a href="https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/mobile-browser-emulator/lbofcampnkjmiomohpbaihdcbjhbfepf?hl=en" target="_blank">mobile browser emulator</a>' and found it effective.</p>
<p><img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/images/blog/mobile-friendly-test/mobile-tester-ext.png" alt="" width="814" height="472"/></p>
<p>After installing the extension you will see its icon at the right side of the bookmarks bar. Visit any site on the main Chrome window, click the red 'm' icon and select the simulating device. A popup window will render the emulated view of the site for the selected device.</p>
<p><img src="/images/blog/mobile-friendly-test/BizCraft-mobile.jpg" alt="" width="1571" height="743"/></p>
<p>If you use Firefox, you may try <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-us/firefox/addon/emuflex/" target="_blank">Emuflex </a>in this purpose.</p>
<p>Did you make your website mobile friendly already? Which tools do you use in testing mobile-friendliness? Please share with us via comments. Thank you for reading.  </p> </div>
